summary:
Topical steroids are most effective in eczematous dermatitis due to reliable anti-inflammatory action without increasing viral replication risk. Their use in herpetic lesions is restricted to late-stage stromal involvement after antivirals and carries significant safety concerns when applied during acute epidermal infections.  
\boxed{B}

The topological steriods' greatest effectiveness lies in managing chronic inflammatory conditions such as eczema rather than actively treating infectious processes involving viruses. In cases related to Herpes simplex virus, especially those affecting mucocutaneous surfaces, application can worsen outcomes unless preceded by adequate antiviral treatment; thus, true therapeutic benefit occurs only under strict indications within non-active phases of injury.\boxed{B}

